REST (Representational State Transfer) remains the most widely adopted API architecture, and for good reason. Its simplicity, coupled with HTTP's ubiquity, makes it an excellent choice for most applications.

### Core REST Principles

**1. Resource-Based**
```
GET    /api/users          # List all users
GET    /api/users/123      # Get specific user
POST   /api/users          # Create new user
PUT    /api/users/123      # Update user
DELETE /api/users/123      # Delete user
```

**2. Stateless Communication**
- Each request contains all necessary information
- No session state stored on server
- Improves scalability and reliability

**3. Standard HTTP Methods**
- GET (read), POST (create), PUT (update), DELETE (remove)
- PATCH for partial updates
- HEAD for metadata only

### Advanced REST Implementation

```typescript
import express, { Request, Response, NextFunction } from 'express';
import { body, validationResult } from 'express-validator';

interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  createdAt: Date;
}

class UserAPI {
  private app: express.Application;

  constructor() {
    this.app = express();
    this.setupMiddleware();
    this.setupRoutes();
  }

  private setupMiddleware() {
    this.app.use(express.json());
    this.app.use(this.rateLimiter);
    this.app.use(this.authenticate);
  }

  private setupRoutes() {
    // List users with pagination
    this.app.get('/api/users', 
      this.validatePagination,
      this.getUsers
    );

    // Get single user
    this.app.get('/api/users/:id', 
      this.validateUserId,
      this.getUser
    );

    // Create user
    this.app.post('/api/users',
      body('name').isLength({ min: 2 }),
      body('email').isEmail(),
      this.createUser
    );

    // Update user
    this.app.put('/api/users/:id',
      this.validateUserId,
      body('name').optional().isLength({ min: 2 }),
      body('email').optional().isEmail(),
      this.updateUser
    );

    // Delete user
    this.app.delete('/api/users/:id',
      this.validateUserId,
      this.deleteUser
    );
  }

  private async getUsers(req: Request, res: Response) {
    const page = parseInt(req.query.page as string) || 1;
    const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string) || 10;
    const offset = (page - 1) * limit;

    try {
      const users = await db.user.findMany({
        skip: offset,
        take: limit,
        orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' }
      });

      const total = await db.user.count();

      res.json({
        data: users,
        pagination: {
          page,
          limit,
          total,
          pages: Math.ceil(total / limit)
        },
        links: {
          self: `/api/users?page=${page}&limit=${limit}`,
          next: page * limit < total ? `/api/users?page=${page + 1}&limit=${limit}` : null,
          prev: page > 1 ? `/api/users?page=${page - 1}&limit=${limit}` : null
        }
      });
    } catch (error) {
      res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
    }
  }
}
```

### REST Best Practices

:::alert
**Critical:** Always version your APIs (e.g., `/api/v1/users`) to maintain backward compatibility as your API evolves.
:::

- **Use nouns, not verbs** in URLs (`/users`, not `/getUsers`)
- **Implement proper status codes** (200, 201, 400, 404, 500, etc.)
- **Support filtering, sorting, pagination** for collections
- **Use HATEOAS** for discoverability (include relevant links in responses)
- **Implement rate limiting** to prevent abuse
- **Provide clear error messages** with helpful details

### REST Performance Optimization

| Technique | Benefit | Implementation Complexity |
|-----------|---------|---------------------------|
| **HTTP Caching** | Reduce server load | Low |
| **ETag support** | Conditional requests | Medium |
| **Compression** | Faster transfers | Low |
| **Connection pooling** | Reuse connections | Medium |
| **CDN integration** | Global distribution | Medium |

