## GraphQL: Query Exactly What You Need

GraphQL revolutionized API development by shifting control to the client, allowing them to request exactly the data they need‚Äînothing more, nothing less.

### Why GraphQL?

**Problem with REST:**
```javascript
// Need user name and posts? Make 2 requests:
GET /api/users/123
GET /api/users/123/posts

// Or create a custom endpoint:
GET /api/users/123/with-posts
```

**GraphQL Solution:**
```graphql
query {
  user(id: "123") {
    name
    email
    posts {
      title
      createdAt
    }
  }
}
```

### Building a Production-Ready GraphQL API

```typescript
import { ApolloServer, gql } from 'apollo-server-express';
import { GraphQLError } from 'graphql';
import DataLoader from 'dataloader';

// Type definitions
const typeDefs = gql`
  type User {
    id: ID!
    name: String!
    email: String!
    posts: [Post!]!
    followers: [User!]!
    followersCount: Int!
  }

  type Post {
    id: ID!
    title: String!
    content: String!
    author: User!
    comments: [Comment!]!
    likesCount: Int!
    createdAt: String!
  }

  type Comment {
    id: ID!
    content: String!
    author: User!
    post: Post!
    createdAt: String!
  }

  input CreatePostInput {
    title: String!
    content: String!
  }

  type Query {
    user(id: ID!): User
    users(limit: Int, offset: Int): [User!]!
    post(id: ID!): Post
    feed(limit: Int): [Post!]!
  }

  type Mutation {
    createPost(input: CreatePostInput!): Post!
    deletePost(id: ID!): Boolean!
    likePost(postId: ID!): Post!
  }

  type Subscription {
    postAdded: Post!
    commentAdded(postId: ID!): Comment!
  }
`;

// Resolvers with DataLoader for N+1 prevention
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    user: async (_: any, { id }: { id: string }, { dataSources, userLoader }: any) => {
      return userLoader.load(id);
    },

    feed: async (_: any, { limit = 10 }: { limit?: number }, { user, db }: any) => {
      if (!user) throw new GraphQLError('Not authenticated');

      return db.post.findMany({
        take: limit,
        orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' },
        where: {
          authorId: { in: user.followingIds }
        }
      });
    }
  },

  User: {
    posts: async (parent: any, _: any, { postLoader }: any) => {
      return postLoader.loadMany(parent.postIds);
    },

    followersCount: async (parent: any, _: any, { db }: any) => {
      // Efficient count query
      return db.follow.count({
        where: { followingId: parent.id }
      });
    }
  },

  Mutation: {
    createPost: async (
      _: any,
      { input }: { input: CreatePostInput },
      { user, db, pubsub }: any
    ) => {
      if (!user) throw new GraphQLError('Not authenticated');

      const post = await db.post.create({
        data: {
          ...input,
          authorId: user.id
        },
        include: { author: true }
      });

      // Publish to subscribers
      pubsub.publish('POST_ADDED', { postAdded: post });

      return post;
    }
  },

  Subscription: {
    postAdded: {
      subscribe: (_: any, __: any, { pubsub }: any) => 
        pubsub.asyncIterator(['POST_ADDED'])
    }
  }
};

// DataLoader setup to prevent N+1 queries
function createLoaders(db: any) {
  return {
    userLoader: new DataLoader(async (ids: readonly string[]) => {
      const users = await db.user.findMany({
        where: { id: { in: [...ids] } }
      });
      return ids.map(id => users.find((u: any) => u.id === id));
    }),

    postLoader: new DataLoader(async (ids: readonly string[]) => {
      const posts = await db.post.findMany({
        where: { id: { in: [...ids] } }
      });
      return ids.map(id => posts.find((p: any) => p.id === id));
    })
  };
}
```

### GraphQL vs REST: The Decision Matrix

| Criteria | REST | GraphQL | Winner |
|----------|------|---------|--------|
| **Learning curve** | Low | Medium | REST |
| **Flexibility** | Low | High | GraphQL |
| **Caching** | Easy (HTTP) | Complex | REST |
| **Over-fetching** | Common | Eliminated | GraphQL |
| **Tooling** | Mature | Growing | REST |
| **Real-time** | Limited | Built-in | GraphQL |
| **File uploads** | Simple | Complex | REST |
| **Versioning** | Explicit | Implicit | REST |

:::alert
**Pro Tip:** Consider using GraphQL for internal APIs where you control clients, and REST for public APIs where simplicity and caching are priorities.
:::

## Event-Driven Architecture: Building Resilient Systems

Event-driven architecture (EDA) represents a fundamental shift from synchronous request-response patterns to asynchronous, loosely-coupled systems that can scale independently.

### The Event-Driven Paradigm

**Traditional Synchronous Flow:**
```
Client ‚Üí API ‚Üí Database ‚Üí API ‚Üí Client
(Client waits for entire chain)
```

**Event-Driven Flow:**
```
Client ‚Üí API ‚Üí Event Bus ‚Üí Background Workers
         ‚Üì
    Immediate Response
```

### Real-World Implementation with Kafka

```typescript
import { Kafka, Producer, Consumer } from 'kafkajs';
import { z } from 'zod';

// Event schemas with validation
const UserCreatedEvent = z.object({
  type: z.literal('user.created'),
  data: z.object({
    userId: z.string(),
    email: z.string().email(),
    name: z.string(),
    timestamp: z.string().datetime()
  })
});

const OrderPlacedEvent = z.object({
  type: z.literal('order.placed'),
  data: z.object({
    orderId: z.string(),
    userId: z.string(),
    items: z.array(z.object({
      productId: z.string(),
      quantity: z.number(),
      price: z.number()
    })),
    total: z.number(),
    timestamp: z.string().datetime()
  })
});

type UserCreatedEvent = z.infer<typeof UserCreatedEvent>;
type OrderPlacedEvent = z.infer<typeof OrderPlacedEvent>;

// Event Publisher
class EventPublisher {
  private producer: Producer;

  constructor(private kafka: Kafka) {
    this.producer = kafka.producer();
  }

  async connect() {
    await this.producer.connect();
  }

  async publishUserCreated(event: UserCreatedEvent) {
    // Validate event
    const validated = UserCreatedEvent.parse(event);

    await this.producer.send({
      topic: 'user-events',
      messages: [{
        key: validated.data.userId,
        value: JSON.stringify(validated),
        headers: {
          'event-type': validated.type,
          'timestamp': validated.data.timestamp
        }
      }]
    });
  }

  async publishOrderPlaced(event: OrderPlacedEvent) {
    const validated = OrderPlacedEvent.parse(event);

    // Use transactions for exactly-once semantics
    const transaction = await this.producer.transaction();

    try {
      await transaction.send({
        topic: 'order-events',
        messages: [{
          key: validated.data.orderId,
          value: JSON.stringify(validated)
        }]
      });

      await transaction.commit();
    } catch (error) {
      await transaction.abort();
      throw error;
    }
  }
}

// Event Consumer
class EmailService {
  private consumer: Consumer;

  constructor(private kafka: Kafka) {
    this.consumer = kafka.consumer({ 
      groupId: 'email-service',
      // Enable auto-commit for at-least-once delivery
      autoCommit: true,
      autoCommitInterval: 5000
    });
  }

  async start() {
    await this.consumer.connect();
    await this.consumer.subscribe({ 
      topics: ['user-events', 'order-events'],
      fromBeginning: false 
    });

    await this.consumer.run({
      eachMessage: async ({ topic, partition, message }) => {
        try {
          const event = JSON.parse(message.value!.toString());

          switch (event.type) {
            case 'user.created':
              await this.sendWelcomeEmail(event.data);
              break;
            case 'order.placed':
              await this.sendOrderConfirmation(event.data);
              break;
          }
        } catch (error) {
          console.error('Error processing event:', error);
          // Implement dead letter queue for failed events
          await this.sendToDeadLetterQueue(message);
        }
      }
    });
  }

  private async sendWelcomeEmail(userData: any) {
    // Email sending logic
    console.log(`Sending welcome email to ${userData.email}`);
  }

  private async sendOrderConfirmation(orderData: any) {
    console.log(`Sending order confirmation for ${orderData.orderId}`);
  }
}
```

### Event-Driven Patterns Comparison

| Pattern | Use Case | Complexity | Example |
|---------|----------|------------|---------|
| **Pub/Sub** | Fan-out notifications | Low | User signup triggers multiple services |
| **Event Sourcing** | Audit trail, time travel | High | Financial transactions |
| **CQRS** | Read/write optimization | Medium | E-commerce product catalog |
| **Saga Pattern** | Distributed transactions | High | Order processing across services |
| **Stream Processing** | Real-time analytics | High | Live dashboards, monitoring |

![Event-Driven Architecture](https://deifkwefumgah.cloudfront.net/shadcnblocks/block/placeholder-dark-2.svg)

### Benefits & Trade-offs

**Benefits:**
- ‚úÖ **Loose coupling** - Services don't need to know about each other
- ‚úÖ **Scalability** - Process events asynchronously at your own pace
- ‚úÖ **Resilience** - System continues working if one service fails
- ‚úÖ **Flexibility** - Easy to add new consumers without changing producers

**Challenges:**
- ‚ö†Ô∏è **Complexity** - More moving parts to manage
- ‚ö†Ô∏è **Debugging** - Distributed tracing required
- ‚ö†Ô∏è **Consistency** - Eventual consistency requires careful design
- ‚ö†Ô∏è **Ordering** - Maintaining event order can be challenging
